    });
}
let autocomplete = Autocomplete::new(ac_commands);
```

Then handle it in the submit handler:
```rust
async fn handle_submit(&mut self, text: String) -> Result<()> {
    match text.trim() {
        "/bench" => {
            self.messages.push(DisplayMessage::System("Running benchmark...".into()));
            // ... benchmark logic
        }
        // ... other commands
        input if input.starts_with('/') => {
            // Check if it's a skill trigger
            if let Some(skill) = self.skills.iter().find(|s| input.starts_with(&s.trigger)) {
                self.inject_skill(skill);
            } else {
                self.messages.push(DisplayMessage::System(
                    format!("Unknown command: {input}")
                ));
            }
        }
        _ => self.send_message(text).await?,
    }
    Ok(())
}
```

The autocomplete filters against both trigger and description, so typing `/ben` will match `/bench` and typing `inference` would also match it because the description contains that word. The dropdown renders at the bottom of the message area as an overlay, capped at 8 visible entries with scrolling.

The core logic counts occurrences of `old_string` and rejects ambiguous matches:

```rust
let count = content.matches(&old_string).count();
if count == 0 {
    return Ok(ToolResult::error(
        "old_string not found in file. Make sure the string matches exactly."
    ));
}
if !replace_all && count > 1 {
    return Ok(ToolResult::error(format!(
        "old_string found {count} times. Provide more context to make it unique, or set replace_all: true."
    )));
}
```

Why this matters: consider a file with two functions:
```rust
fn process(input: &str) -> String {
    input.to_uppercase()
}

fn transform(input: &str) -> String {
    input.to_lowercase()
}
```

If the model tries to edit with `old_string: "input: &str"`, that matches both function signatures. Without the ambiguity check, it would silently modify the first occurrence, potentially breaking the wrong function. The error message `"found 2 times"` guides the model to include more context:

```json
{
    "old_string": "fn process(input: &str) -> String {",
    "new_string": "fn process(input: &str, options: &Options) -> String {"
}
```

The `replace_all: true` escape hatch exists for legitimate bulk replacements like renaming a variable across a file. The model must explicitly opt in, which prevents accidental mass modifications.

One edge case: `old_string == new_string` is rejected early because it's always a model error (the model thinks it needs to make a change but provided identical strings). This saves a file read/write cycle.

The ErrorManager uses NWPathMonitor to track connectivity and automatically adjusts the app's offline state:

```swift
private func startNetworkMonitoring() {
    networkMonitor.pathUpdateHandler = { [weak self] path in
        DispatchQueue.main.async {
            self?.updateNetworkStatus(path.status == .satisfied)
        }
    }
    networkMonitor.start(queue: networkQueue)
}

private func updateNetworkStatus(_ isConnected: Bool) {
    let wasOffline = isOffline
    isOffline = !isConnected

    if wasOffline && isConnected {
        networkLogger.info("Network connectivity restored")
    } else if !wasOffline && !isConnected {
        networkLogger.notice("Network connectivity lost - entering offline mode")
        handle(.networkUnavailable, context: "Network connectivity lost")
    }
}
```

The key design decision is that `.networkUnavailable` has `.info` severity:

```swift
var severity: ErrorSeverity {
    switch self {
    case .networkUnavailable: return .info  // Not a real error
    // ...
    }
}
```

In the `handle` method, `.info` severity errors are logged but NOT shown to the user:
```swift
func handle(_ error: SerenaError, context: String? = nil) {
    logError(error, context: context)
    let record = ErrorRecord(error: error, context: context)
    errorHistory.insert(record, at: 0)

    // Only show non-info errors to user
    if error.severity != .info {
        currentError = error
        isShowingError = true
    }
}
```

The recovery action reinforces offline-first:
```swift
case .networkUnavailable:
    return .ignore("Continue using offline mode")
```

And the user guidance message explicitly reassures:
```swift
case .networkUnavailable:
    return "\(baseMessage)\nGood news: All AI processing happens locally, so you can continue chatting normally."
```

This is critical for user confidence. Many users assume AI = cloud. The error system must actively communicate that Serena works fully offline. The network monitor is still useful for features like web search and VA integrations that do need connectivity.
